"""Algorithm classics — sorting variants, search patterns, classic problems with full solutions."""
LESSONS=[
    ('What is heapsort?','Sorting via max-heap. Build heap from array (O(n)). Repeatedly: swap root (max) with last, shrink heap, sift down. O(n log n) worst case (better worst than quicksort). In-place. Not stable. Used when worst-case O(n log n) needed + memory limited (vs mergesort\'s O(n) extra).'),
    ('What is counting sort?','Non-comparison sort for integers in known range. Count occurrences of each value, then output in order. O(n + k) where k = value range. Stable. Linear time — beats comparison sorts O(n log n) lower bound. Limitation: huge value range = wasted space.'),
    ('What is radix sort?','Sort by digits left-to-right or right-to-left, using stable counting sort per digit. O(d * (n + k)) where d = digit count. For fixed-width keys, this is linear in n. Use for: integers, strings of bounded length. Beats comparison sorts for large n.'),
    ('What is bucket sort?','Distribute items into buckets based on value range, sort each bucket (often insertion sort), concatenate. O(n) average if values uniformly distributed. Works well for: floats in [0,1), uniformly-distributed integers. Bad if data skewed (one bucket gets everything).'),
    ('What is insertion sort?','Iterative sort. For each element, shift larger elements right + insert in correct position. O(n²) worst case but O(n) on nearly-sorted. Stable. In-place. Used as fallback for small arrays (≤10) inside quicksort/mergesort — constants beat O(n log n) at small n.'),
    ('What is the stable sorting property?','Equal elements maintain their relative order. Mergesort, insertion sort, counting sort: stable. Quicksort, heapsort: NOT stable. Matters when sorting by multiple keys progressively (sort by minor key first, then major key — only correct if stable).'),
    ('What is QuickSelect?','Find kth smallest in O(n) average. Like quicksort but only recurse into the side containing position k. O(n²) worst, fixable with median-of-medians for O(n) deterministic. Python: heapq.nlargest(k, arr) often easier for top-k.'),
    ('What is Tarjan\'s strongly connected components algorithm?','Find SCCs in directed graph in O(V+E). DFS with discovery + low-link numbers. Stack of currently-visiting nodes. When low_link == disc_num at a node, pop stack down to that node — those form an SCC. Single pass (Kosaraju needs two DFS).'),
    ('What is Kruskal vs Prim for MST?','Both compute Minimum Spanning Tree. Kruskal: sort all edges + add smallest that doesn\'t form cycle (union-find). O(E log E). Better for sparse graphs. Prim: grow tree from a start node, adding cheapest connecting edge each step. O((V+E) log V) with heap. Better for dense graphs.'),
    ('What is the Knuth-Morris-Pratt (KMP) algorithm?','Substring search in O(n + m). Preprocesses pattern into a "failure function" telling you, on mismatch, the longest proper prefix that\'s also a suffix — shift pattern without rescanning text. Beats naive O(nm) for repetitive patterns.'),
    ('What is Rabin-Karp algorithm?','String matching via rolling hash. Hash the pattern, hash each window of text, compare hashes (cheap), confirm by char compare on hash match. O(n+m) average. Sliding window: remove old char from hash, add new char. Great for multi-pattern matching.'),
    ('What is the Aho-Corasick algorithm?','Multi-pattern string matching. Build trie of all patterns + failure links. Single pass through text, finds ALL occurrences of any pattern. O(n + sum_of_pattern_lengths + matches). Used in: virus scanning, intrusion detection.'),
    ('What is segment tree?','Tree data structure for range queries (sum, min, max, etc.) over an array with point updates. Each node stores aggregate over its range. Build O(n). Query + update both O(log n). Use when: many range queries + many point updates. Variant: lazy propagation for range updates.'),
    ('What is Fenwick tree (BIT)?','Binary Indexed Tree. Compact data structure for prefix sums with point updates. O(log n) update + query. Simpler + faster constants than segment tree but limited to invertible operations (sum, XOR). Use for: many "sum of range" queries with updates.'),
    ('What is the union-find with path compression?','Disjoint Set Union. find(x) follows parent pointers to root; path compression sets every visited node to point directly to root. union(x, y) joins by attaching smaller tree under larger (union by rank). Together: O(α(n)) ≈ O(1) per op. Foundation of Kruskal, connectivity, equivalence partitions.'),
    ('What is reservoir sampling?','Pick K uniformly random items from a stream of unknown length, using O(K) memory. For each item i (1-indexed): if i ≤ K, store. Else, with probability K/i, replace a random kept item. Each item ends up with same K/n probability. Use for: sampling from streams, log files, big datasets.'),
    ('What is the Boyer-Moore voting algorithm?','Find majority element (appears >n/2 times) in O(n) time, O(1) space. Track candidate + count. On each elem: if count==0, set candidate. If matches candidate, count++; else count--. At end, candidate is the majority (if one exists; verify with second pass if not guaranteed).'),
    ('What is the sweep line algorithm?','Process events sorted by one coordinate (often x). Maintain active set as line "sweeps." Used for: rectangle overlap, segment intersections, closest pair, skyline problem. Often O(n log n). Examples: meeting room scheduling, computing union of intervals.'),
    ('What is meet in the middle?','Split problem in halves, solve each separately, combine. Reduces O(2^n) brute force to O(2^(n/2)). Classic: subset sum — enumerate subsets of first half + second half separately, hash one + check the other. Used in: collision attacks, larger-than-naive search problems.'),
    ('What is dynamic programming bottom-up vs top-down?','Both DP styles. Top-down: recursion with memoization (cache results, recurse for unmemoized). Bottom-up: iterative table fill, computing base cases first. Top-down: cleaner code, only computes needed subproblems. Bottom-up: better cache locality, no recursion overhead. Pick by problem shape.'),
    ('What is the bitmask DP?','DP where state is a bitmask of "which items are used/visited." Use when N is small (≤20-25). 2^N states. Example: Traveling Salesman dp[mask][last] = min cost visiting cities in mask, ending at last. O(2^N * N²).'),
    ('What is the Manhattan vs Euclidean distance?','Manhattan: sum of axis-aligned distances |x1-x2| + |y1-y2|. Like walking city blocks. Euclidean: sqrt((x1-x2)² + (y1-y2)²). Straight-line. Manhattan often used in grid problems (chess pieces, game maps), Euclidean for continuous space.'),
    ('What is line sweep for closest pair?','Sort points by x. Maintain "strip" of points within current min distance. For each new point, only check points in strip (within min-d on both axes). O(n log n) total. Beats naive O(n²) for distance problems.'),
]
